WEBVTT

00:05.804 --> 00:09.074
<i>[pleasant music]</i>

00:09.108 --> 00:10.610
[sniffing]

00:10.643 --> 00:14.080
Ah, nothing like bacon
and eggs in the morning.

00:14.112 --> 00:17.283
It's a hearty meal that holds
you together for the whole day.

00:17.315 --> 00:20.085
It's a combination so obvious
that it's been around

00:20.118 --> 00:22.387
for as long as
both foods existed.

00:22.420 --> 00:25.658
Humans naturally loved
these foods together,

00:25.690 --> 00:29.461
so they became
a staple of breakfast.

00:29.495 --> 00:31.697
Or did they?

00:31.730 --> 00:34.500
What if I were to tell you
that the traditional combination

00:34.533 --> 00:37.436
of bacon and eggs isn't part
of our natural history,

00:37.469 --> 00:40.138
but is instead
a corporate conspiracy

00:40.171 --> 00:43.141
orchestrated by society's
true puppet masters?

00:43.174 --> 00:45.577
It isn't a breakfast
for champions.

00:45.610 --> 00:49.214
It's a breakfast for sheeple.

00:49.247 --> 00:52.217
<i>[electronic music]</i>

00:52.250 --> 00:58.991
<i>♪</i> ♪

01:02.962 --> 01:05.565
We think that a lot of
commonplace things

01:05.598 --> 01:08.901
are the way they are because of
collective free choice,

01:08.934 --> 01:10.902
when in fact, sometimes,

01:10.935 --> 01:13.672
one or two people alone

01:13.705 --> 01:16.341
made a decision
and created something

01:16.375 --> 01:19.779
that is now taken for granted
as part of society...

01:19.812 --> 01:21.747
Just part of life.

01:21.780 --> 01:24.617
Here's the real story
behind bacon and eggs.

01:24.649 --> 01:27.786
It all begins
with Sigmund Freud.

01:27.819 --> 01:31.657
<i>Or rather, his nephew,
Edward Bernays.</i>

01:31.690 --> 01:35.828
<i>Bernays is credited as the
"Father of Public Relations",</i>

01:35.860 --> 01:37.996
the product of a time
when the world

01:38.030 --> 01:40.333
had become just small enough

01:40.366 --> 01:43.536
that you could manipulate
a lot of people at once

01:43.568 --> 01:45.737
because of the way that
advertising, news,

01:45.771 --> 01:49.508
and radio could reach a large
number of people quickly.

01:49.541 --> 01:51.777
Bernays took advantage
of mass media

01:51.809 --> 01:54.479
not with the intention
to inform,

01:54.512 --> 01:57.649
but with the intention
to control.

01:57.682 --> 02:01.520
<i>In the 1920s,
Ed Bernays asked a doctor</i>

02:01.553 --> 02:04.657
<i>who worked at his agency
whether a breakfast should be</i>

02:04.690 --> 02:08.026
<i>heavy or light, and the doctor
pretty much said,</i>

02:08.059 --> 02:09.995
<i>"I guess heavy
would be better."</i>

02:10.029 --> 02:12.398
<i>Bernays then had that doctor</i>

02:12.430 --> 02:15.567
<i>get 4,500 other doctors
to confirm that.</i>

02:15.601 --> 02:18.638
All of them concurred
that a heavy breakfast

02:18.670 --> 02:21.941
was better for the health
of the American people.

02:21.973 --> 02:24.410
Then, Bernays lobbied newspapers

02:24.442 --> 02:27.345
to publish that all these
doctors were saying

02:27.378 --> 02:29.482
you should eat
a big ol' breakfast.

02:29.514 --> 02:32.317
But he wasn't doing this
to improve public health.

02:32.351 --> 02:35.821
He was doing this because
Beech-Nut Packing Company,

02:35.853 --> 02:38.023
<i>a major supplier of bacon,</i>

02:38.056 --> 02:40.859
<i>was paying him to do it.</i>

02:40.893 --> 02:43.329
The sale of bacon went up,

02:43.362 --> 02:46.364
and I still have a letter

02:46.398 --> 02:48.434
from Bartlett Arkell,

02:48.466 --> 02:50.902
president of Beech-Nut
Packing Company,

02:50.936 --> 02:52.905
telling me so.

02:52.937 --> 02:55.374
<i>So we collectively,
as a country,</i>

02:55.406 --> 02:58.511
<i>agreed that bacon was our
breakfast meat of choice.</i>

02:58.543 --> 03:01.047
<i>But we didn't freely
make that choice at all.</i>

03:01.079 --> 03:03.348
<i>And that's just breakfast.</i>

03:03.382 --> 03:05.450
<i>Our lives are full of decisions
that we think</i>

03:05.483 --> 03:07.719
<i>we make of our own free will.</i>

03:07.752 --> 03:08.953
