12:48.249 --> 12:50.385
<i>- And she wasn't the only one.</i>
- Whoo!

12:50.418 --> 12:51.553
- How do you think you did?

12:51.586 --> 12:53.288
- I think I did pretty...
Pretty great.

12:53.321 --> 12:55.324
If you could do it again,
would you have

12:55.356 --> 12:57.458
preferred to have been assigned
a different tea?

12:57.491 --> 12:59.394
- No.
<i>Studies have shown that</i>

12:59.427 --> 13:02.297
<i>sometimes we're happier
when we don't have a choice.</i>

13:02.329 --> 13:04.665
Well, for two points,

13:04.698 --> 13:07.601
you... you win nothing.

13:07.635 --> 13:10.338
This game is actually
more about investigating

13:10.371 --> 13:12.440
the mind, so in reality,

13:12.473 --> 13:16.143
the real winner today
is everyone.

13:16.177 --> 13:18.380
Thanks for playing,
and remember,

13:18.413 --> 13:20.649
no matter where you live
or who you are,

13:20.682 --> 13:25.486
it's always...
both: "Tea Time!"

13:25.520 --> 13:28.390
- Damn it, I just found
another word.

13:28.423 --> 13:31.393
<i>[subtle electronic music]</i>

13:31.425 --> 13:35.429
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:35.462 --> 13:37.498
So, it's not always preferable

13:37.531 --> 13:39.767
to be in the driver's seat
of your life.

13:39.800 --> 13:42.503
Sometimes, the pressure
to make a decision

13:42.536 --> 13:46.073
can cause you to dwell on
the options you didn't choose

13:46.106 --> 13:48.175
and hinder your performance.

13:48.208 --> 13:50.478
But what if there's
a difference between

13:50.511 --> 13:53.748
the physical process
of making a decision

13:53.781 --> 13:56.517
and your consciousness
being aware

13:56.550 --> 13:58.452
that a decision has been made?

13:58.486 --> 14:02.124
What if all your decisions
are made by someone...

14:02.156 --> 14:04.759
No, something else...

14:04.793 --> 14:09.031
A split second before you're
aware you've made them?

14:09.063 --> 14:16.005
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:22.242 --> 14:23.310
<i>[buzzer blares]</i>
Hmm.

14:23.343 --> 14:25.579
<i>This task seems easy enough.</i>

14:25.612 --> 14:28.449
<i>Just push either button
before the light comes on.</i>

14:28.482 --> 14:31.452
<i>[buzzer blares]</i>
Mm. Mm.

14:31.486 --> 14:32.754
<i>[buzzer blares]</i>
Ah!

14:32.786 --> 14:35.189
<i>So why is it so difficult?</i>
Wow!

14:35.222 --> 14:37.125
<i>It's difficult because
this machine</i>

14:37.308 --> 14:38.809
<i>is actually reading my mind.</i>

14:38.893 --> 14:41.428
<i>It knows when I decide
to push a button</i>

14:41.461 --> 14:44.431
<i>and lights them up before
I can actually push one.</i>

14:44.465 --> 14:46.401
How does it feel
when it's happening?

14:46.433 --> 14:48.702
- It feels like...<i>
- [buzzer blares]</i>

14:48.735 --> 14:51.273
Like, right then.

14:51.306 --> 14:53.675
It already knew.<i>
[buzzer blares]</i>

14:53.707 --> 14:56.577
I'm trying to not have
my mind read.

14:56.610 --> 14:57.912
<i>[buzzer blares]</i>
Ah!

14:57.945 --> 14:59.614
<i>Here's how the box works.</i>

14:59.647 --> 15:03.752
<i>My decision to push a button doesn't
begin when I think it does.</i>

15:03.784 --> 15:07.888
<i>It's actually preceded by subconscious
activity, I'm not aware of</i>

15:07.922 --> 15:09.990
<i>But that the machine can detect.</i>

15:10.023 --> 15:13.494
<i>Now the machine isn't predicting
which button I will push,</i>

15:13.527 --> 15:18.465
<i>it's determining when I am about
to push one, before I know it.</i>

15:18.499 --> 15:20.734
<i>For the first few minutes,
I push buttons,</i>

15:20.768 --> 15:22.903
<i>and the box records my brain
activity</i>

15:22.936 --> 15:26.573
<i>learning which behaviors follow
which subconcsious processes.</i>

15:26.606 --> 15:27.874
<i>♪</i> ♪

15:27.908 --> 15:31.045
<i>Eventually, the box can know
what I'm about to do,</i>

15:31.079 --> 15:33.048
<i>before even I do.</i>

15:33.080 --> 15:36.051
In other words, it can read
my subconscious mind

15:36.084 --> 15:37.886
and tell me what
I was going to do

15:37.918 --> 15:40.487
before I know
I was going to do it.

15:40.521 --> 15:42.791
That's the part
that freaks me out.

15:42.824 --> 15:45.527
<i>This is called
a free will experiment</i>

15:45.560 --> 15:49.830
<i>because it begs the question of
what "free will" actually is.</i>

15:49.864 --> 15:51.965
<i>If the subconscious
knows what you're doing</i>

15:51.999 --> 15:54.969
<i>before you do it,
is it really your decision,</i>

15:55.002 --> 15:57.739
<i>or do you just think
it's your decision?</i>

15:57.772 --> 15:59.441
<i>[buzzer blares]</i>
Wow.

15:59.474 --> 16:00.642
[laughs]

16:00.675 --> 16:02.577
I'm trying to surprise it.

16:02.609 --> 16:04.044
<i>[buzzer blares]</i>
Ah.

16:04.077 --> 16:06.648
The interesting thing is
to see, like,

16:06.681 --> 16:09.484
for instance, that you become
closer to the machine,

16:09.517 --> 16:11.453
and you definitely speed up.

16:11.485 --> 16:12.653
I feel very competitive.

16:12.686 --> 16:14.556
I don't want my mind to be read.

16:14.589 --> 16:16.056
<i>I find this process
frustrating...</i>

16:16.090 --> 16:17.459
<i>[buzzer blares]</i>
Mm!

16:17.492 --> 16:19.394
<i>Even though I know how the box
works.</i>

16:19.426 --> 16:20.903
<i>But what if you didn't
know what the box did</i>

16:20.927 --> 16:23.697
before you tried it?

16:23.730 --> 16:25.609
I want to introduce you to
Moran, and this is Diana

16:25.633 --> 16:27.402
from the YouTube channel
Physics Girl,

16:27.435 --> 16:29.604
one of my favorite
YouTube channels.

16:29.637 --> 16:31.138
Michael, stop.

16:31.172 --> 16:33.074
Derek, thanks for being here.

16:33.106 --> 16:35.843
I'm very excited to
introduce you to Moran Cerf

16:35.877 --> 16:37.679
- from Northwester.
- Nice to meet you.

16:37.711 --> 16:40.080
And he's brought his box.

16:40.114 --> 16:42.816
<i>Diana and Derek
have scientific minds.</i>

16:42.850 --> 16:45.854
<i>But they have not been told
what the box really does.</i>

16:45.887 --> 16:49.858
<i>Moran explains a deceptively
easy game.</i>

17:02.170 --> 17:03.738
- So we could...
- The lights are on,

17:03.771 --> 17:04.839
don't touch it.
- Yeah.

17:04.871 --> 17:06.540
<i>Once the box begins to beat</i>

17:06.573 --> 17:08.877
<i>their conscious decision-making
to the punch,</i>

17:08.909 --> 17:11.678
<i>will they be able to figure out
what's going on?</i>

17:11.712 --> 17:13.579
Do I look a bit
like a jellyfish?

17:13.613 --> 17:15.749
- You feel comfortable?
- Great. I feel amazing.

17:15.781 --> 17:18.551
Okay. You can start.

17:18.586 --> 17:21.556
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

17:21.589 --> 17:24.492
<i>For the first 15 minutes,
the box calibrates</i>

17:24.523 --> 17:26.593
<i>and learns how
the subject's mind acts</i>

17:26.627 --> 17:29.464
<i>before making a decision.</i>

17:29.496 --> 17:32.132
<i>Then, the fun begins.</i>

17:32.166 --> 17:33.201
<i>[buzzer blares]</i>

17:33.234 --> 17:35.669
<i>♪</i> ♪

17:35.703 --> 17:36.671
<i>[buzzer blares]</i>

17:36.704 --> 17:39.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:39.674 --> 17:40.683
- Before? <i>
- [buzzer blares]</i>

17:40.707 --> 17:42.543
Yeah.

17:42.577 --> 17:44.179
<i>[buzzer blares]</i>

17:44.212 --> 17:46.915
<i>Both of our subjects seem
increasingly confused</i>

17:46.947 --> 17:49.184
<i>and frustrated.
[buzzer blares]</i>

17:49.216 --> 17:50.784
[laughs]

17:50.818 --> 17:53.955
<i>I know exactly how they feel.</i>

17:53.987 --> 17:56.623
<i>[buzzer blares]</i>
[laughs]

17:56.657 --> 17:58.535
It's hard 'cause sometimes,
like, the light comes on

17:58.559 --> 17:59.803
while I'm going
to push it, you know?

17:59.827 --> 18:01.029
- Yeah, yeah.

18:01.061 --> 18:02.696
Well, Moran, do you want
to tell him?

18:02.730 --> 18:05.934
So, this box here

18:05.966 --> 18:07.835
is reading your brain activity

18:07.869 --> 18:10.672
and tries to predict not which
button you're gonna press,

18:10.705 --> 18:12.874
but when, and then turn
the lights on

18:12.907 --> 18:14.576
just before you
press the button.

18:14.609 --> 18:17.512
This is predicting when
I'm gonna make the decision.

18:17.544 --> 18:19.013
What?
- Yeah.

18:19.045 --> 18:20.747
This is amazing.

18:20.781 --> 18:22.917
I definitely noticed the
lights going on often

18:22.949 --> 18:24.751
when I was going
to hit the buttons.

18:24.784 --> 18:26.253
- Mm-hmm.
- But also there were times

18:26.286 --> 18:28.222
when, like, I wasn't gonna
make any choice,

18:28.255 --> 18:30.190
and they just went on,
so I was like, well...

18:30.224 --> 18:32.260
- Why? How do you know?
- [laughing] Right.

18:32.292 --> 18:33.861
- What?
- How do you know that?

18:33.895 --> 18:35.629
Maybe the lights
just stopped your brain

18:35.663 --> 18:37.574
from telling you that you were
about to make a choice.

18:37.598 --> 18:40.201
It's not just, "Oh,
he's about to push it",

18:40.234 --> 18:43.705
but it's "he is about to become

18:43.737 --> 18:46.707
aware that he is going
to push the button".

18:46.741 --> 18:48.719
I'm trying to think, like, I'm
still trying to out-think you.

18:48.743 --> 18:49.952
Like, I'm trying to be like,
"Oh, I'm gonna

18:49.976 --> 18:51.121
"push the left button,
I'm gonna...

18:51.145 --> 18:52.714
Wait, no, I'm gonna
do the right".

18:52.746 --> 18:54.290
It's interesting that you
put it that way.

18:54.314 --> 18:56.717
Because really, it's not about
out-thinking us,

18:56.751 --> 19:00.989
it's about out-thinking
yourself.

19:01.022 --> 19:05.527
The implications of this
are kind of chilling.

19:05.560 --> 19:07.729
We could find things
out about you that

19:07.762 --> 19:10.064
you didn't know yourself
or didn't wanna say.

19:10.097 --> 19:11.733
We could tell you
things like,

19:11.765 --> 19:14.167
"Which of these two paintings
will you prefer?"

19:14.201 --> 19:15.637
- Mm-hmm.
- How do you really

19:15.669 --> 19:17.638
feel about someone,
or imagine

19:17.671 --> 19:19.273
using this for dating.

19:19.307 --> 19:21.776
Because it's reading
your subconscious mind...

19:21.809 --> 19:23.711
- Mm-hmm.
- We might be able to tell that

19:23.744 --> 19:27.282
you prefer someone
that you don't actually

19:27.314 --> 19:29.016
think you do.

19:29.050 --> 19:32.052
Well, that sounds scary.

19:32.086 --> 19:33.154
[laughter]

19:33.186 --> 19:35.089
But... but at the same time,

19:35.121 --> 19:37.292
I feel like I...
I don't know.

19:37.324 --> 19:39.561
I'm such a human, Michael,
I feel like

19:39.593 --> 19:41.061
my humans response is like,
"Okay,

19:41.094 --> 19:43.030
"there's a process
my brain goes through.

19:43.063 --> 19:44.698
"I get it. You learned it.

19:44.732 --> 19:48.670
But it's still my brain,
it's still my process".

19:48.703 --> 19:51.773
- Denial.
- Is...

19:57.344 --> 20:00.881
I... I like to call it
"Limitations" of free will.

20:00.915 --> 20:02.358
And by the way, we know that
you're gonna have

20:02.382 --> 20:03.984
chicken salad
for tomorrow's dinner.

20:04.017 --> 20:05.362
[laughter]
Yes, that's very clear.

20:05.386 --> 20:06.888
It's very good
at predicting that.

20:06.920 --> 20:08.789
- Yeah.
- [laughing]

20:08.822 --> 20:11.792
<i>[subtle electronic music]</i>

20:11.826 --> 20:13.861
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:13.894 --> 20:16.164
Like falling dominoes,

20:16.196 --> 20:18.632
a whole chain of things
has led up

20:18.666 --> 20:20.335
to now, this very moment.

20:20.368 --> 20:22.936
In your life, those dominoes
might be

20:22.969 --> 20:26.340
<i>your parents, your childhood,
the books you've read,</i>

20:26.373 --> 20:28.642
<i>your friends, things that have
influenced you,</i>

20:28.676 --> 20:29.977
<i>what you had for breakfast,</i>

20:30.011 --> 20:33.147
how you felt this afternoon.

20:33.179 --> 20:36.618
Everything has led up to now,
that final domino,

20:36.650 --> 20:40.321
but how it falls, well,
that's your choice, right?

20:40.353 --> 20:42.356
Or is it?
[sighs]

20:42.389 --> 20:45.792
Moran's box kind of questions
some of that.

20:45.826 --> 20:50.031
If your brain can tell us
what you're going to do

20:50.063 --> 20:52.766
before you even know
you're going to do it,

20:52.800 --> 20:55.203
is your conscious mind
actually being controlled

20:55.235 --> 20:56.937
<i>by your subconscious mind?</i>

20:56.971 --> 21:00.274
<i>And if your subconscious
can be fooled,</i>

21:00.307 --> 21:02.310
<i>then who is actually in charge?</i>

21:02.342 --> 21:04.811
Do you truly have free will?

21:04.844 --> 21:07.280
Or are you just...

21:07.313 --> 21:10.118
like a puppet?

21:10.150 --> 21:13.086
A puppet who thinks

21:13.119 --> 21:15.657
it has no strings?

21:15.689 --> 21:17.725
Does your conscious, aware self

21:17.757 --> 21:19.793
just take credit for things

21:19.827 --> 21:22.330
your unconscious body's already

21:22.362 --> 21:23.997
decided to do?

21:24.031 --> 21:26.834
[laughs] Well, more research
needs to be done.

21:26.867 --> 21:28.403
But what we do know is that

21:28.436 --> 21:32.939
things you normally wouldn't
consider part of you

21:32.973 --> 21:36.377
are a gigantic part of you.

21:36.409 --> 21:40.247
I think Kermit the Frog
said it best:

21:40.281 --> 21:44.018
"Although I'm not sure exactly
what Jim Henson did,

21:44.051 --> 21:47.989
whatever it was,
it really moved me".

21:51.058 --> 21:54.028
<i>[electronic music]</i>

